=== TASK ===
# Settings & Preferences (Tenant)

## Overview
Create the Tenant-level Settings & Preferences module for OfficeInventory AI. This page enables administrators to configure global, tenant-scoped policies and defaults that drive how audits are created, processed, and governed across all sites. It should provide editors for default export schemas, inference thresholds, review SLAs, storage lifecycle policies, and webhook endpoints. The UI must be robust, safe, accessible, and visually aligned with the project’s design system. All data flows must be secure, auditable, and isolated per tenant. All code must guard against null/undefined values before calling array methods and follow the runtime safety rules described in the project constraints.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A centralized Tenant Settings hub for enterprise administrators to configure:
  - Default Export Schemas: define the structure of export CSV/JSON/PDF reports used across audits.
  - Inference Thresholds: global confidence thresholds, auto-accept rules, and human-review queuing logic.
  - Review SLAs: auto-assignment rules, escalation timelines, and reviewer pools for quality assurance.
  - Storage Lifecycle: lifecycle policies for uploaded images and audit artifacts (retention, archiving, purge).
  - Webhooks & Integrations: manage endpoint URLs, authentication headers, test calls, and retry policies.

Goals:
- Provide a single source of truth for tenant-wide governance of audits.
- Enable safe, scalable customization without impacting other tenants.
- Offer clear visibility into current policies, with inline validation and actionable controls.
- Provide export/import capabilities for schema definitions and policies to facilitate onboarding and migration.

Features connected:
- Exports: Generates output according to the tenant default export schema.
- Inference and Review: Drives AI processing queues and reviewer assignment on new audits.
- Storage Lifecycle: Determines retention and archival behavior for assets.
- Webhooks: Enables external integrations for events (audit created, item detected, review completed, etc.) and tests live endpoints.
- Access control: Ensures only authorized admins per tenant can modify settings.

UI elements and how they should look:
- Default Export Schema Editor: A form-based editor with:
  - Toggles to enable/disable fields
  - Drag-and-drop or reorderable column definitions
  - Validation indicators and live preview of the export structure
- Inference Settings: Card with numeric fields and switch controls:
  - Global confidence threshold (0-100 or 0-1 scale)
  - Auto-accept deterministic rules
  - Queuing behavior for low-confidence items
- Review SLA Settings: Rules interface with:
  - Auto-assign rules, escalation timelines, SLA metrics
  - Reviewer pools (selectable from user groups) and fallback rules
- Storage & Retention: Policy editor with:
  - Lifecycle tiers, retention durations, purge windows
  - Per-type policies (images, reports, logs)
- Webhooks & Integrations: Endpoint management:
  - List of webhook endpoints with status, last test, retry policy
  - Create/Edit forms with URL validation, auth header field, payload templates
  - Test button to simulate a delivery and display results
- Visual guidance:
  - Consistent card-based layouts with generous spacing (24–32px)
  - Clear section headings and metadata
  - Action pills and primary/secondary CTAs using the green accent
  - Inline validation messages and helpful tooltips
- API integrations:
  - Persist to backend services via REST/GraphQL endpoints
  - Validate inputs before submission
  - Reflect server-side validation errors with user-friendly messages

## Components to Build
- TenantSettingsPage: Main container with sections for each settings domain.
- ExportSchemaEditor
  - Fields: enabled toggle, list of columns, column order, field types
  - Drag-and-drop reordering (or up/down controls)
  - Live preview pane of exported schema
- InferenceSettingsPanel
  - Inputs: threshold, auto-accept toggle, max auto-accept items per batch
- ReviewSLAPanel
  - Auto-assign rules editor, escalation timelines, reviewer pool selector
- StorageLifecyclePanel
  - Lifecycle policy builder with tiers, retention durations, purge rules
- WebhooksPanel
  - Endpoints list with create/edit/delete
  - TestEndpointModal for on-demand test
  - Retry policy controls and signing/auth headers
- ValidationBadge/InlineValidation
- StatusBadge for webhook/test results
- ConfirmDialog for destructive actions (delete, reset to defaults)
- Utility: EmptyState, LoadingState, and ErrorState components

Technical details:
- All forms must support initial data loading, with safe defaults (e.g., data ?? []) and useState defaults like useState<T[]>([]) where appropriate.
- Ensure all arrays are guarded: (items ?? []).map(...), Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
- Use strict typing (TypeScript) for props and state to reduce nullability risk.
- Implement optimistic UI updates only after server acknowledgment; otherwise, revert safely on error.
- Provide accessible ARIA attributes for interactive elements.
- Ensure all API calls include proper error handling and user feedback.

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Framework: React (TypeScript) with a modern state management approach (e.g., React Query or SWR for data fetching, or a lightweight context-based store for settings).
- State management:
  - useState with proper defaults for all array/object state
  - useEffect for data hydration with safe guards
  - Validation logic for each field with inline messages
- UI components:
  - Card-based layout with elevated surfaces and hover states
  - Forms with soft, rounded inputs and clear focus styles
  - Drag-and-drop support for Export Schema Editor (optional fallback to up/down controls if DnD is not feasible)
  - Modals for tests and confirmations
- Data loading:
  - Fetch tenant settings on mount
  - Persist changes with debounced updates where appropriate to reduce server load
- Accessibility:
  - Keyboard navigable controls
  - Clear focus outlines and aria-labels
- Security:
  - Ensure sensitive fields (e.g., webhook secrets) are treated securely with proper masking in UI, never logging raw values
- Runtime safety:
  - Guard all array methods and nested property access as per the runtime safety rules
  - Robust defaulting for any API responses
- Testing:
  - Unit tests for validators and utility functions
  - Integration tests for API endpoints (mocked) and UI flows
  - End-to-end test scenario: update export schema, set inference threshold, configure a webhook, and verify persistence

### Backend
- API endpoints (REST or GraphQL) to support:
  - GET tenant/settings
  - PUT/PATCH tenant/settings (bulk or per-section)
  - Webhook endpoint management (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)
  - Webhook test trigger
  - Export schema import/export (export schema payload, import validation)
  - Storage lifecycle policy CRUD
  - Inference policy CRUD
  - Review SLA policy CRUD
- Database schema considerations:
  - Tenant-scoped configurations stored in a dedicated settings table with JSON fields for schemas
  - Tables for:
    - export_schemas (tenant_id, schema_id, schema_definition)
    - inference_settings (tenant_id, threshold, auto_accept, max_auto_accept_per_batch)
    - review_sla (tenant_id, rules, escalation_times)
    - storage_policies (tenant_id, policy_definitions)
    - webhooks (tenant_id, name, url, method, headers, auth_type, secret_masked, enabled, last_test_status, retry_policy)
- Validation:
  - Validate input shapes server-side
  - Ensure tenant isolation for all reads/writes
  - Enforce field constraints and sensible defaults if missing
- Security:
  - Authenticate/authorize admin users
  - Encrypt sensitive webhook data at rest
  - Audit logs for changes to settings

### Integration
- Data flow:
  - On page load, frontend fetches tenant settings from GET tenant/settings
  - User edits sections; frontend validates, then PATCHs the updated sections
  - Webhooks test triggers a live endpoint test and reports results on the UI
  - Export schema changes affect downstream export generation logic
- Consistency:
  - All updates are versioned and auditable
  - Use optimistic updates with rollback on error
  - Centralized error handling and toast/notification system
- Data shaping:
  - Use consistent JSON schemas for export definitions
  - Use normalized types for thresholds (0-1 or 0-100) with clear UI hints
  - Normalize durations (e.g., days/hours) for retention policies

## User Experience Flow
1. Admin logs in and navigates to Settings & Preferences (Tenant).
2. Page loads with sections collapsed or in tabs; each card shows current values and last-modified metadata.
3. User expands Default Export Schema Editor:
   - Edits fields, toggles, and order; previews resulting schema in real-time
   - Saves changes; UI indicates success and shows updated preview
4. User navigates to Inference Settings:
   - Adjusts global confidence threshold and auto-accept rules
   - Applies changes; queue behavior updates are reflected in the next run
5. User opens Review SLA Settings:
   - Configures auto-assign rules, escalation timelines, reviewer pools
   - Validates and saves; changes ripple to new audits
6. User configures Storage Lifecycle:
   - Sets retention periods, archiving rules, purge windows
   - Confirms and saves
7. User adds/updates Webhooks:
   - Creates a new endpoint or edits existing one
   - Enters URL, method, headers, and test payload
   - Runs a test; results shown in UI; saves if successful
8. Admin reviews a summarized dashboard with status indicators for each setting domain
9. All changes are persisted to backend with audit trail entries

## Technical Specifications

- Data Models: 
  - TenantSettings (tenant_id, export_schema, inference_settings, review_sla, storage_policies, webhooks, updated_at, version)
  - ExportSchema (schema_id, tenant_id, fields, enabled, created_at, updated_at)
  - InferenceSettings (tenant_id, threshold, auto_accept, max_auto_accept_per_batch, updated_at)
  - ReviewSLAs (tenant_id, rules, escalation_times, updated_at)
  - StoragePolicies (tenant_id, policies_json, updated_at)
  - Webhooks (webhook_id, tenant_id, name, url, method, headers_json, auth_type, secret_masked, enabled, retry_policy_json, last_test_status, updated_at)
- API Endpoints: 
  - GET /api/tenant/settings
  - PATCH /api/tenant/settings (partial updates per section)
  - POST /api/tenant/webhooks
  - PUT /api/tenant/webhooks/{id}
  - DELETE /api/tenant/webhooks/{id}
  - POST /api/tenant/webhooks/{id}/test
  - POST /api/tenant/export-schemas/import
  - GET /api/tenant/export-schemas/export
  - PATCH /api/tenant/storage-policies
  - PATCH /api/tenant/inference-settings
  - PATCH /api/tenant/review-sla
- Security: 
  - OAuth2 / SSO-enabled admin access
  - Role-based access control (RBAC) with tenant isolation
  - TLS in transit; AES-256 at rest
  - API-level input validation and CSRF protection for web-based edits
- Validation:
  - All inputs validated server-side and client-side
  - Validation schemas for each setting type
  - Data normalization and defaults if missing
- Null-safety rules:
  - Always use data ?? [] for array results
  - Guard array operations with Array.isArray or (items ?? []).map(...)
  - Initialize useState with typed empty arrays where appropriate

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Tenant page loads with all five sections present and correct initial values from the backend
- [ ] Default Export Schema Editor supports enabling fields, reordering columns, live preview, and persists correctly
- [ ] Inference Settings allow setting threshold and auto-accept rules with validation and persistence
- [ ] Review SLA Settings support auto-assign, escalation timelines, and reviewer pool selection with correct persistence
- [ ] Storage Lifecycle policies support retention/archival/purge configurations with per-type granularity
- [ ] Webhooks panel supports create/edit/delete/test, displays status, and persists changes
- [ ] All API calls guard against null/undefined and pass strict server-side validation
- [ ] UI adheres to the design system: color usage, typography, spacing, and component behavior
- [ ] Security and access controls validated; only admins can modify settings
- [ ] End-to-end flow works: update settings, trigger a test webhook, and reflect changes consistently

## UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
---
Visual Style

Color Palette:
- Primary background: Soft light gray (#F5F6F8) for main workspace, with slightly darker gray (#E8E9EC) for card backgrounds
- Accent color: Vibrant lime green (#C9FF52) for highlighting key actions, events, and active states
- Secondary colors: Pure white (#FFFFFF) for card and modal surfaces, deep black (#18191A) for navigation and summary panels, and mid-gray (#B6B7BA) for dividers and muted text
- Text: Dark gray (#232323) for primary text, lighter gray (#6B6B6B) for secondary text, and white (#FFFFFF) on dark backgrounds
- Additional accents: Red (#FF5E5E) for warning or error states, orange (#FFC85E) and sky blue (#6ECFFF) for secondary status and tags
- Color relationships: High contrast between accent green and muted neutrals for clear focus; black panels create visual anchor points

Typography & Layout:
- Font family: Clean, geometric sans-serif (e.g., Inter, SF Pro, or Circular)
- Font weights: Regular for body, bold for headings, medium for labels and CTAs
- Hierarchy: Large, bold headings; medium-weight subheads; lighter secondary labels and metadata
- Spacing: Generous padding and margin between cards and sections (24–32px), with consistent vertical rhythm
- Alignment: Left-aligned text, center-aligned key metrics, and edge-to-edge card layouts
- Treatments: Subtle use of color and weight for emphasis; iconography paired with text for clarity

Key Design Elements

Card Design:
- Card styling: Rounded corners (16–24px radius), mild drop shadows for elevation, white or very light gray backgrounds
- Borders: Minimal or none, relying on shadow and spacing for separation
- Hover/active: Subtle shadow intensification or light outline; accent green highlight for selected cards
- Visual hierarchy: Prominent title, secondary metadata, compact icons and tags at the bottom

Navigation:
- Top bar: Pill-shaped, black with white and accent green highlights for active items
- Sidebar: Minimal vertical icon stack, outlined with subtle dividers
- Active states: High-contrast color (green or white on black) and pill backgrounds for current section
- Collapsible/expandable: Not explicitly shown, but navigation elements are designed to support modular expansion

Data Visualization:
- Chart styles: Not directly visible, but summary panels hint at card-style stat blocks with bold numerals and compact labels
- Visual treatments: Use of accent colors for status, white/black backgrounds for strong separation
- Patterns: Inline mini-charts or status pills likely for quick-glance metrics

Interactive Elements:
- Button styles: Rounded pill-shaped buttons, filled (accent green or black) or outlined, minimal iconography
- Form elements: Soft, rounded fields with subtle shadows or outlines, clear focus states
- Hover effects: Mild shadow intensification, color fill transitions, and micro-interactions (icon movement/scale)
- Micro-interactions: Subtle, reinforcing clarity and responsiveness

Design Philosophy
This interface embodies:
- A modern, minimalist, and professional aesthetic with high clarity and focus on actionable elements
- Design principles of simplicity, whitespace, and visual hierarchy to reduce cognitive load and drive efficiency
- Rounded, approachable shapes and high-contrast accenting to guide user attention
- User experience goals centered on frictionless navigation, quick scanning, and confident action-taking with clear status and feedback
- Visual strategy prioritizing enterprise trust, approachability, and clear modularity for scalable workflows

